| Released       = June 8, 1983
| Format         = [[single (music)|7" single]], [[12"]], [[compact audio cassette|cassette]]
| Recorded       = 1983
| Genre          = [[Alternative rock]]
| Length         = 4:06
| Label          = [[I.R.S. Records]]
| Producer       = [[Don Dixon (musician)|Don Dixon]] & Mitch Easter
| Last single    = "Radio Free Europe" (Hib-Tone version)<br>(1981)
| This single    = "Radio Free Europe" (I.R.S. version)<br/>(1983)
| Next single    = "[[Talk About the Passion]]"<br/>(1983)
}}
R.E.M. signed to I.R.S. Records in 1982. I.R.S. asked R.E.M. to re-record "Radio Free Europe" in 1983 for their debut album, ''Murmur''.<ref>Pond, Steve. "[http://www.rollingstone.com/artists/rem/articles/story/5938674/cover_story_in_the_real_world In the Real World]". ''Rolling Stone''. [[December 3]], [[1987]]. Retrieved on [[May 19]], [[2008]].</ref> The band agreed, because they had felt that they'd improved significantly since the original 1981 sessions.  The new version has some slightly different lyrics and a slower tempo, and is not as well-liked with the band as the original; indeed, the liner notes for the 1988 compilation album ''Eponymous'' (which the original Hib-Tone version is featured on) stated that "[[Mike Mills|Mike]] and [[Jefferson Holt|Jefferson]] think this one [referring to the Hib-Tone version] crushes the other one like a grape." Peter Buck has also stated that he "[didn't] think we captured it the way we did on the single."  Original producer Mitch Easter also commented on the re-recording, saying it was "more pro, but a little too sedate."<ref>Black, p. 74</ref>

The re-recorded version of "Radio Free Europe" was the first single from ''Murmur''. It was the first R.E.M. single to reach the charts, peaking at number 78 on the ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' singles chart and remaining on the chart for five weeks.<ref>"[http://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/6596224/radio_free_europe Radio Free Europe]". ''Rolling Stone''. [[December 9]], [[2004]]. Retrieved on [[May 21]], [[2008]].</ref> The single also reached number 25 on the ''Billboard'' [[Hot Mainstream Rock Tracks|Mainstream Rock Tracks]] chart.<ref name="Allmusic singles">[http://www.allmusic.com/cg/amg.dll?p=amg&sql=11:09fexqtgld0e~T51 R.E.M. - Charts & Awards - Billboard Singles]. Allmusic.com. Retrieved on [[May 21]], [[2008]].</ref>

